---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const meta = {
  title: "Deciding When to Retire: When Timing Becomes Critical",
  category: "Planning",
  dateLabel: "Jan 2026",
  readTime: "10 min read",
  author: "Cutler Capital Management",
  image: "/images/placeholders/research/retire-timing.jpg",
  excerpt:
    "Retirement timing is rarely one decision. It’s a chain of linked assumptions—expenses, health, income sources, and how long savings must last.",
};
---

<BaseLayout title={`${meta.title} | Research`}>
  <main id="main">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <div class="container article-hero__inner">
        <div class="article-meta">
          <a class="kicker" href="/research/">Research &amp; Insights</a>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="cat">{meta.category}</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="article-title">{meta.title}</h1>
        <p class="article-dek">{meta.excerpt}</p>

        <div class="byline">
          <span class="author">{meta.author}</span>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="date">{meta.dateLabel}</span>
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true">•</span>
          <span class="time">{meta.readTime}</span>
        </div>

        <div class="hero-media" aria-hidden="true">
          <img src={meta.image} alt="" loading="eager" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="article-body">
      <div class="container article-grid">
        <article class="prose">
          <p>
            Deciding when to retire may not be one decision but a series of decisions and calculations. You’ll need to
            estimate anticipated expenses, identify income sources, and decide when to begin tapping each stream—
            Social Security, pensions, and retirement accounts.
          </p>

          <h2 id="early">Thinking about early retirement?</h2>
          <p>
            Retiring early means fewer earning years and less accumulated savings. It also means more years in which your
            savings must produce income. And retirement can last a long time.
          </p>

          <div class="callout">
            <p class="callout-title">Why inflation matters</p>
            <p>
              Inflation has time to compound against you. If inflation averages 3% annually, purchasing power can be cut roughly
              in half over a couple decades—meaning a “fixed” retirement income may feel smaller each year.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="health">Health, longevity, and coverage</h2>
          <p>
            Timing decisions interact with health and insurance. Medicare generally begins at 65. If you retire earlier and
            don’t have retiree health coverage, you may need to model health costs before Medicare.
          </p>

          <h2 id="delay">Delaying retirement</h2>
          <p>
            Postponing retirement gives you more time to save, potentially receive employer contributions, and reduce how long
            you need withdrawals to cover expenses. Even without new contributions, delaying the start of withdrawals may help
            a portfolio last longer.
          </p>

          <h2 id="phased">Phased retirement: the best of both worlds</h2>
          <p>
            Some employers offer phased retirement programs, letting employees reduce work hours while beginning certain benefits.
            This can smooth the transition and extend runway.
          </p>

          <h2 id="key-points">Key decision points</h2>
          <div class="table-wrap" role="region" aria-label="Key decision points table">
            <table class="table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Milestone</th>
                  <th>Age</th>
                  <th>Don’t forget…</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Tap tax-deferred savings without early penalty</td>
                  <td>59½*</td>
                  <td>Income taxes still apply to pre-tax dollars</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Eligible for early Social Security</td>
                  <td>62</td>
                  <td>Claiming early reduces each monthly payment</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Eligible for Medicare</td>
                  <td>65</td>
                  <td>Contact Medicare 3 months before turning 65</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Full retirement age (Social Security)</td>
                  <td>66–67</td>
                  <td>After FRA, earned income no longer reduces benefits</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p class="small muted">*Age 55 may apply for certain employer-plan distributions upon termination of employment.</p>

          <h2 id="assumptions">Check your assumptions</h2>
          <p>
            Start early, revise often. As you approach retirement, revisit assumptions: spending, inflation, longevity, taxes,
            and market returns. Your plan should remain workable across different market environments—not just one perfect scenario.
          </p>

          <hr class="sep" />

          <div class="article-footer">
            <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/research/">← Back to Research</a>
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/contact/">Talk with us</a>
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside class="aside" aria-label="On this page">
          <div class="aside-card">
            <p class="aside-title">On this page</p>
            <nav class="toc" aria-label="Table of contents">
              <a href="#early">Early retirement</a>
              <a href="#health">Health + Medicare</a>
              <a href="#delay">Delaying retirement</a>
              <a href="#phased">Phased retirement</a>
              <a href="#key-points">Key decision points</a>
              <a href="#assumptions">Check assumptions</a>
            </nav>
          </div>

          <div class="aside-card">
            <p class="aside-title">Disclaimer</p>
            <p class="small muted" style="margin:0;">
              Educational content for build validation. Not individualized advice.
            </p>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

